<h2 class="section-header">Making Your Decision: A Framework</h2>

<p>Reading twenty venue descriptions creates as many questions as answers. Here's how to narrow your list:</p>

<h3 class="decision-framework-header">Start With Capacity</h3>

<p>Be honest about your real guest count. If you're inviting 150 people, assume 120-130 will actually attend. This immediately eliminates venues that can't accommodate your numbers or would feel empty with them.</p>

<h3 class="decision-framework-header">Consider Your Timeline</h3>

<p><strong>Planning 8-12 months out (2026 wedding)?</strong> Focus on venues with good mid-week availability or less famous properties that book shorter windows.</p>

<p><strong>Planning 12-18+ months out?</strong> You have access to prime dates at even the most requested venues.</p>

<h3 class="decision-framework-header">Prioritize Experience Over Setting</h3>

<p>The most beautiful venue in Italy will disappoint if they can't execute your celebration properly. Consider:</p>

<ul class="decision-list">
<li>Do they have onsite accommodation or reliable nearby options?</li>
<li>Can they handle your guest count comfortably?</li>
<li>Do they offer weather backup that doesn't compromise your vision?</li>
<li>What's included vs. what requires outside vendors?</li>
</ul>

<h3 class="decision-framework-header">Match Budget to Reality</h3>

<p>These venues range from €50,000 total celebrations to €500,000+. Be realistic about what your budget accommodates, including:</p>

